To write the probability density function (PDF) for a uniform distribution, we need to determine the parameters of the distribution. 

For a uniform distribution \( U(a, b) \), the PDF is given by:

\[
f(x) = \begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{b - a} & \text{for } a \leq x \leq b \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

Given the problem:
- The age of cars is uniformly distributed from 0.5 years to 9.5 years.
- Thus, \( a = 0.5 \) and \( b = 9.5 \).

First, calculate \( b - a \):
\[
b - a = 9.5 - 0.5 = 9
\]

Now, the PDF is:
\[
f(x) = \begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{9} & \text{for } 0.5 \leq x \leq 9.5 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

